BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Print Lab - "Gyotaku" The Art of Fish Printing
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260411T130000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260411T160000
UID:260328UvPpnWcEYECVsXQyLTOEIA
DESCRIPTION:Schedule\n\nSaturday\, April 11\, 2026 1:00 PM – 4:00 PM\n\n
 Location\n\nRoom 208\n\nExperience Level\n\nAll Levels\n\nEvent Category: 
 Printmaking\n\nAge\\(s\\)\n\n16\\+\n\nRegistration Cost:\n\n$40\n\nMateria
 ls Fee:\n\nIncluded\n\nTotal Registration Cost:\n\n$40\n\nIn honor of the 
 Cherry Blossom Festival time of year\, explore the ancient art of Gyotaku 
 fish printing!\n\nAbout the Class\n\nRoll up your sleeves and join us for 
 a special pop-up Saturday afternoon Print Lab! Our mission is to explore a
  creative arts technique socially with our community. Print Lab is not a t
 raditional class\, but an affordable art-making experience. We welcome you
  to print\, play and experiment with an activity to create something uniqu
 e in our printmaking studio! In honor of the Cherry Blossom Festival time 
 of year\, explore the ancient art of Gyotaku fish printing! Gyotaku \\(gyo
 =fish\, taku=rubbing\\) is a traditional Japanese method of printing fish.
  This practice dates back to the mid-1800’s\, when fishermen wanted a wa
 y to document the fish they caught at sea. Pronounced “ghe-yo-tah-koo”
  the process involves applying inks or pigments directly to the fish\, and
  this inked fish impression is then carefully pressed and rubbed onto pape
 r.  In Japan\, fish rubbings became a very accurate way to preserve and r
 ecord the species and size of a catch. Still popular today as a form of na
 ture printing\, it is practiced by sportsmen and artists alike. Experience
  a rare demonstration of gyotaku printing and try communal printmaking! We
  will have an assortment of real fish “catches” to share and print tog
 ether. Each participant will have the opportunity to make and take home 2-
 3 prints using ink and watercolor on Japanese paper. No printmaking experi
 ence is necessary. Light refreshments will be provided.
LOCATION:Sonoma Community Center
URL:https://sonomacommunitycenter.org/programs/print-lab-gyotaku-the-art-o
 f-fish-printing/
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Sheep Shearing Day
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260411T110000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260411T140000
UID:260328LH1OHNzTFU-iXw768i8W-g
DESCRIPTION:**Experience “Sheep to Sweater” at Petaluma Adobe’s Shee
 p Shearing Day!**\n\nHow does wool come off sheep? How does raw wool turn 
 into yarn? Come to the Petaluma Adobe State Historic Park between 11 a.m. 
 and 2 p.m. on Saturday\, April 11th and find out! Heritage breed sheep fro
 m local farm animal rescue Flat Broke Farm will be losing their winter coa
 ts under the expert guidance of shearer John Sanchez. After the sheep are 
 sheared\, you can have fun learning how to turn the raw wool into yarn\, t
 he first steps to making a sweater. Volunteers will teach how to card and 
 drop spin wool as *rancho* workers would have in the 1830’s.  Docents w
 ill be on site to give guided tours\, so bring a picnic and spend the day 
 at the Petaluma Adobe State Historic Park.\n\nAdmission fee: $3.00 for adu
 lts 18 and older\, children 6 to 17 are $2.00\, 5 and under are free. Stat
 e Park Historian\, Distinguished Veteran and 4th Grade Adventure Passes ar
 e accepted for this event. Petaluma Adobe State Historic Park is located a
 t 3325 Adobe Road on the east side of Petaluma. California State Parks sup
 ports equal access. Prior to arrival\, visitors with disabilities who need
  assistance should contact: Petaluma Adobe State Historic Park (707) 762-4
 871.
LOCATION:Petaluma Adobe State Historic Park
URL:https://www.parks.ca.gov/EventDetails/18414
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
